From: andreas@orion.mgen.uni-heidelberg.de ()
Subject: Re: xterm so slow .... why ?
Date: Mon, 25 Oct 93 19:45:31 GMT

cosc19v2 (cosc19v2@menudo.uh.edu) wrote:

: While I did not have any such problem with SUN3/50, 60
: (either mono or color),
: My 386pc/25 with 8M running linux (p12)  suffers from xterm slowness.
: It scrolls so slow that it really bothers (editing with vi is
: a real pain).  My pc has cirrus logic chipset with 1M (ISA).
: I configured X11 in 1024x768x256 mode.

: Is this because of 386cpu is slow ? (but if so, why even more slower
: old SUNs don't have such problem ? ).
: I experimented it with Cyrix 486 Rx2-50 chip.
: Since the chip runs at 50M inside, at least it helps (editing with
: vi is not that painful), but when the whole screen scrolls (ex when
: using more), it is still  unacceptable.

: Or, is the VGA board not fast enough ?

Probably.

: Will S3 chipset VGA board (such as Farenheit) get rid of this problem ?

Most likely if you exchange the svga server into the s3 one.

: I am running only one xterm (rxvt) and fvwm.
: Is it because I am using slightly bigger font (should be 16 pt, or 18pt) ?

: Please give me some suggestions.

I began using X with a Ati graphics ultra card with the svga server using
the Ati VGA part (this was on a 486/33 with 8 MB). This had a slow sreen
output. When I exchanged the svga server into the the x8514scale server,
which uses the accelerated 8514a part of the Ati card, my display became
very fast. I do now have a second computer with linux. A 386DX-33 with
8 MB RAM and a ET4000 card. This seems to have a much faster screen than
my original setup with Ati VGA and the svga server.

Andreas

