From: andras@cyber.net (Andras Radics)
Subject: What is Linux (was: Linux Community Divided ?)
Date: 26 Oct 1993 02:02:33 GMT

Someone listed possible "agendas" of different Linux supporters.
Here is mine.

Linux is a great opportunity for "doing Unix right".  I hope to see
Linux grow to embody the functionality of current Unix systems, but be
more efficient, use less memory, be faster, and friendlier.  Where the
commercial vendors don't have incentive and/or opportunity to spend time
re-writing the OS, many developers are constantly tuning and improving
Linux (eg., file systems, networking, device drivers, utilities, etc).
Linux is well on its way to providing more bang per CPU mips than
most other systems.

I would like to see binary compatibility with DOS, Windows, and other
Unixes (BSD, SVR3, etc.) -- mostly for my own convenience.  If I could
use all the my programs and utilities from one environment, I would never
leave Linux.  But I would also like to see new, neat ideas implemented
and standardized upon (like the /proc filesystem, or a possible
/dev/bitblit interface); I'd really like some of the concepts of Plan9
show up eventually.

Linux is more than an OS, it's a movement -- a chance to contribute to
and modify a system under development, and have those changes be made
part of the standard.  Everyone with a suggestion is welcome, and
programming talent is never turned away :-).

And an extra Thank You to those who've pioneered this effort!


Andras
-- 
Andras Radics
andras@cyber.net

