From: mikep@iastate.edu (Michael K Patterson)
Subject: Re: What is Linux (was: Linux Community Divided ?)
Date: Tue, 26 Oct 1993 02:36:46 GMT

In <2ai0fp$4hh@news.cerf.net> andras@cyber.net (Andras Radics) writes:

>Someone listed possible "agendas" of different Linux supporters.
>Here is mine.

>Linux is a great opportunity for "doing Unix right".  I hope to see
>Linux grow to embody the functionality of current Unix systems, but be
>more efficient, use less memory, be faster, and friendlier.  Where the
>commercial vendors don't have incentive and/or opportunity to spend time
>re-writing the OS, many developers are constantly tuning and improving
>Linux (eg., file systems, networking, device drivers, utilities, etc).
>Linux is well on its way to providing more bang per CPU mips than
>most other systems.

Well, most commercial vendors that are serious about their products make sure
that their products run at least a little faster than their competitors. I 
can't speak for them, cause I'm not them, so any additional speed is them 
being generous ;) My point being, they DO have incentive....

>I would like to see binary compatibility with DOS, Windows, and other
>Unixes (BSD, SVR3, etc.) -- mostly for my own convenience.  If I could
>use all the my programs and utilities from one environment, I would never
>leave Linux.  But I would also like to see new, neat ideas implemented
>and standardized upon (like the /proc filesystem, or a possible
>/dev/bitblit interface); I'd really like some of the concepts of Plan9
>show up eventually.

Hmm. this is the point I mostly wanted to comment on. As much as I would like
to see "wing commander" being run in linux, I seriously doubt it would happen
for a variety of reasons. In other words... as much as I hate it, I'm not 
throwing away dos yet.

As for the compatibility-with-everything question, it's been worked on for
quite a while by quite a number of people for quite a few machines. Emulation
of other processes, software, etc is a common project... But having one OS 
supporting "all" OSes in all ways is a bit much. If it happens, I'll be happy
and impressed ;) (get to work, slave programmers! *WHIP* *WHIP*) 

>Linux is more than an OS, it's a movement -- a chance to contribute to
>and modify a system under development, and have those changes be made
>part of the standard.  Everyone with a suggestion is welcome, and
>programming talent is never turned away :-).

Amen. Good place for them CS students to show off what they've learned ;) This
is one of the most important facets of free unixes... anyone can have one, 
anyone can learn to use it, and anyone can contribute when they have got
something usable.

>And an extra Thank You to those who've pioneered this effort!

You've got a lot of people on that list.... And a lot more to be put on it. 


>Andras
